voice_to_text: My wife is mad I didn't sleep on the couch after she told me to. Last Thursday, I sold my gaming P C for $800 without telling her first. I've had that thing since college, built it myself sophomore year with my roommate, spent every penny from my summer job on it. But I barely touched it in the past two years, maybe turned it on twice. Meanwhile, our a C complete completely died during a 95 degree heat wave and the repair company quoted us $750. We had exactly $200 in our checking account and payday wasn't until next Friday, nine days away. I posted the PC on Facebook Marketplace at 9:00am with detailed spec, send photos. By two PM, some college kid showed up at our door with 800 dollar cash, didn't even try to negotiate. I handed 750 dollars to the AC guy who was scheduled for three PM, kept 50 dollars for gas money and thought I was being responsible and smart. My wife got home from work at 6 and walk straight into my office like she always does. She froze in the doorway. Where's your computer? Did someone break in? I explained the whole situation, showed her the AC receipt on the counter, even pulled up the Facebook messages on my phone. She stared at the receipt for a solid 10 seconds. Then her face went red and she said, you sold something worth $800 without even texting me. That's a major financial decision. I Tried explaining it was technically mine from before we got married. It was collecting dust and we desperately needed the a C fixed or we'd be sleeping in a sauna. She cut me off mid sentence. I don't care whose it was. Legally we're married now. You should have called me at lunch. I would have said yes, but you didn't even ask. Then came the punishment. Sleep on the couch tonight. I actually laughed out loud because I thought she was joking. We have a guest bedroom right across the hall with a full size bed that literally nobody uses except when her parents visit twice a year. Why would I fold my 6.2 frame onto our tiny uncomfortable couch when there's a perfectly good empty room 10 feet away? I told her that exact logic and he got even more furious. The couch is the entire point. It's supposed to be uncomfortable. That's how you show you're actually sorry for what you did. I refused. This wasn't me coming home drunk or forgetting her birthday or anything that actually deserved punishment. I fixed our a C during a heat wave with my own prop.

voice_to_text: Pretty. I grabbed my pillow and phone charger and went straight to the guest room. Slept absolutely amazing. Actually way better than our 10 year old saggy mattress that desperately needs replacing but we can't afford right now. At 6:00am, she barged into the guest room without knocking and turned on the lights. Why didn't you sleep on the couch like I specifically told you to? I was genuinely confused, but maybe she was joking again because there's a bedroom right here with a real bed. Why would anyone choose a couch? She sat down on the edge of the bed and her tone got dead serious. Gave me this whole speech about marriage and respect, about how when one spouse tells the other to sleep on the couch, they're supposed to do it exactly as instructed, not find a comfortable loophole, not use logic to get around it. Just do it to prove you respect a relationship and feel genuine remorse for your actions. I sat up and looked at her. I was being punished for using my own gaming PC to fix our broken AC during summer. What exactly am I supposed to feel remorse about? That was apparently the completely wrong thing to say. They came to take me off the island. I looked at them in despair, unable to say a single word.

voice_to_text: I can see him, Marcus. That day, my son was planning to go watch a game. But he received a call from me in the middle of the trip telling him the news. His study abroad application was approved. I told him to come home immediately, but as he turned around, he was stopped by a passing white police officer. The officer asked him to place his hands on the steering wheel. But Jack wanted to place his phone on the passenger seat first, so I can see him. A child about to study abroad was beaten to death in the street. The court's conclusion was that Jack was suspected of reckless driving and the police were just doing their job. This result was hard for me to accept. I spent every day in sorrow. Although I was a member of Parliament, I couldn't get the correct verdict for my son. Since the law couldn't bring justice, I decided to take matters into my own hands to avenge my son. I started gathering information everywhere. Finally, a mysterious person give me enough evidence. The notes detailed the incident and even included information on other victims and their families. I thought that with the evidence, I could clear my son's name. But that night, high ranking officials showed up at my door, threatening me to stop investigating. They bluntly told me this case was covered up by the police chief as part of a bribe to the mayor. For the chief's Reelection I knew I couldn't fight them alone, so I found the families of other victims and decided to expose the bribe money to the public. That night, we blew up a car by the roadside, distracting the bodyguards at the mayor's house. Then we rushed upstairs to the safe. But as soon as we reached the top, we encountered the nanny coming out of the bathroom. Luckily, she acted like she didn't see us and went back to her room. We then opened the safe and packed all the money into our bag. Everything went smoothly, but just as we were about to escape with the money, we were caught by the mayor himself. We were so scared that we raised our hands. The mayor pulled off my mask. Someone stepped forward to stop him, but was shot by the mayor. Another companion shot and killed the mayor. We quickly grabbed the money and continued to run. But we didn't expect that. As soon as we got into the car waiting for us, we were stopped by another mysterious person.

voice_to_text: During the long jump competition, I carried Jenny straight to the farthest spot and no one else could see me at all. Just like that, Jenny easily broke the world record. Then it was her opponent's turn to compete. This time I stood right in front of her to block the way. With my interference, she ended up with a terrible score. The next event was the discus throw, which happened to be her opponent's special. She could casually throw it more than 10 meters away. The discus even hit my head by accident. Luckily I had superpowers to heal myself. But the next second she threw a javelin, and the javelin seemed to have a tracking system locked right onto me. Next was the running race. I came up behind the opponent and slapped her on the butt, causing her to miss the start signal, but she was way too fast. She quickly caught up again, so I went to the finish line to wait for her and stuck out my foot to trip her, but she still managed to take first place. The next event was pole vault, another event her opponent was great at. Just as she jumped, I snapped her pole in half. When Jenny's turn came, I grabbed the pole to help her, and she easily cleared the bar during the high jump. Soon as the opponent jumped over, I knocked the bar down, leaving her completely confused. When Jenny jumped, I gave her a Push from below, and she successfully took first place. The final event was the relay race, but the blue team's members were much stronger than ours. Sure enough, as soon as the race started, my teammates fell far behind, so I secretly took a soda bottle and a hot dog. Then I also grabbed a flower. That's when the blue team realized their baton had been replaced with a soda bottle, and the rest of their batons were replaced with hot dogs and flowers, so they had to run back to get their real batons. But the blue team's captain was incredibly fast. She quickly caught up, so I had to stop her by force before she reached the finish line. Watching her run in place right before the line, everyone around was completely puzzled. In the end, Jenny crossed the finish line first and finally won the first trophy of her life.

voice_to_text: The trap had no bait at all, yet the lobster crawled inside as if offering itself up, it willingly let the fisherman capture it. After being taken to the seafood market, a local chef happened to purchase it. But while prepping the lobster, he noticed a strange fluid dripping from underneath. He flipped it over to take a closer look, and in the next instant, some creature blasted water straight into his face. Caught off guard and disgusted, the chef instantly lost the mood to work and told his assistant to finish the cleanup. Trying to free one hand to wipe the counter, the assistant casually handed the lobster to the young apprentice beside him. When the apprentice crushed the shell, she also got sprayed all over. She didn't think much of it and walked away after the lobster was flushed down the drain. She had no idea that this tiny moment would trigger a disaster for the entire city. That night, the chef suddenly felt drained and dizzy. Assuming he was just over tired, he decided to clock out early, but collapsed halfway home. As his legs gave out, black blood poured from his mouth. He died instantly. The assistant who touched the lobster was rushed to the ICU the next morning, but doctors had no clue how to treat the bizarre symptoms, could only watch him die in agony. Determined to find the cause, Doctor Anna questioned the restaurant manager, but he was just as clueless, only remembering That the chef handled a lobster that day, and the assistant and apprentice tossed it into the grinder afterward. Then both died horribly, and the remaining apprentice called in sick earlier that morning. Hearing this, Anna immediately asked for her address, hoping to get more details. But the apprentice was already dead with the exact same symptoms. It became obvious the source had to be the lobster. Anna collected the assistant's blood and dripped it onto a slide, then cut her finger and mixed the two samples together. Under the microscope, she saw his blood swarming with Marine Vibrio, devouring blood cells at terrifying speed. Sight sent a chill down her spine. But what puzzled her even more, humans are supposed to be naturally resistant to Vibrio, and no known ocean strain has ever been lethal to humans. Yet this one was different. Could dodge white blood cell attacks and produce toxins once mixed with human blood. Anna felt lucky she discovered it early, because if it ever spread, the consequences would be unimaginable.

Even the veteran professor who spent decades studying the sea has never seen anything like this, let alone the intern, Kelly. Yet unexpectedly, Kelly is the one who uncovers the cause of the accident. Back at the coastal station, she finds a video message left by her friend before the disaster, but she missed it because she was out drinking that night. The guilt of losing her last chance to speak to her best friend crushes her. But soon she notices something unusual in the video. Right before the recording ends, a white light rises outside the window, the same glow as the deep sea light paired with the same shrill noise. To test her theory, Kelly extracts both audio samples, the one from the message and the one from the deep. The comparison shows they match almost perfectly. She refuses to believe anything supernatural exists in the ocean. Their argument escalates and they part on bad terms. However, Professor Seagle overhears and makes a New discovery. When he gets home, he receives whale footage sent by kit comparing the two. The same white light and bizarre noise appear again. Tests confirm the match. The professor realizes she wrongfully blamed Kelly. Too proud to apologize herself, she asks Seagull to deliver the footage to Kelly on his way to a global ocean conference. Seagull acknowledges Kelly's findings. The tension between Kelly and the professor finally eases. They are getting closer to the truth. Luckily, just before take off, Seagull receives the institute's emergency warning. He drags Kelly away from the danger zone. Minutes later, the tsunami slams into the coast. Watching her entire station wiped out so effortlessly leaves Kelly trembling. At least she is alive. Others aren't so fortunate. Blocks of seabirds suddenly flee inland in panic and the shoreline retreats dramatically. Anyone who has lived through a tsunami knows this is the omen of a coming catastrophe. People sprint wildly. Drivers slam the gas. Those on foot wish they could grow wings, but nothing can outrun the fury of the sea. Three coastal nations are struck simultaneously. The Global Ocean Organization immediately takes action. voice_to_text: He finally uncovers what drove the killer whales into madness. Inside the barnacles, he discovers a strange fungus no scientist has ever documented. Driven by curiosity, kit dissects the stranded orca and finds the same organism embedded inside its brain. Yet orcas are mammals. They shouldn't share a fungus with crustaceans like barnacles. So kit concludes the fungus mutated the barnacles and triggered the whale's bizarre behavior. Following the trail, kit searches for the fungus's origin near the spot where the orca attacked the fishing vessel. But he stumbles upon something unexpected. Connecting the locations forms the whale's migration path, meaning the source must lie somewhere along that route. The next morning, kit and his team begin tracking humpback for safety. He slips into the water only after the giants fall asleep. Even then, seeing those massive bodies suspended upside down in the dark terrifies him. Every motion he makes is painfully cautious, terrified of waking these unpredictable Titans. But the mishap still happened. Just as he tries to attach a tracking camera, the humpbacks jolt awake, nearly stopping his heart. Luckily, they don't attack. Instead, the entire pod surges toward the surface. His teammate on the boat notices and reacts instantly. Firing up the engine to escape, kit drops all his weights and kicks upward with everything he has, climbing aboard seconds before the whale strikes. His partner slams the throttle forward, and they speed away from danger. Days later, following the signal, kit retrieves the detached tracker plugs. It into the laptop and freezes in shock. The humpbacks weren't drifting at all. They were lined up, diving deeper and deeper. But humpbacks must surface every 10 minutes to breathe. They shouldn't survive dives that extreme. The only explanation. Something down there is calling them. Sure enough, as the pod continues descending, everyone is left speechless. Far below, in the pitch black water, a glowing white mass pulses with light and emits eerie sounds. When the whales reach it, they stop sinking, almost as if they're worshipping the light. The footage freezes here, leaving the researchers bewildered. Every scientific record insists nothing in the deep can glow uninterrupted. And certainly not produce such powerful acoustic waves. What they don't realize is, days earlier, when the camera first captured that white glow, something even more unsettling had already occurred. Beneath an ocean research vessel. The sea suddenly churned like boiling water, accompanied by a sound no one should hear underwater. The entire ship shook violently. Before the crew could react, the intact vessel was swallowed whole by the ocean in an instant.

voice_to_text: The first time she saw her owner, Doug, she instinctively knew he was the human meant for her. And Doug seemed to feel the same connection. From that day forward, they were inseparable. She fully believed Doug cared for her just as much, until that one day she picked up the underwear left by the girl who visited Doug yesterday. To her surprise, Doug's girlfriend seemed thrilled to see it, but the underwear wasn't hers. Doug claimed it was a Christmas present. His girlfriend reminded him that it was only January. Somehow that tiny detail sparked a fight. After that moment, she never saw Doug's girlfriend again. One night, Doug got drunk. She stayed by his side, only to hear him say she had ruined his life. He said if she hadn't brought random things home, his girlfriend wouldn't have discovered anything. Watching Doug cry while calling his girlfriend, she wanted to comfort him and grab the ball on the back. But the next moment, she accidentally broke Doug's most treasured item. Doug scolded her. Immediately, she felt certain she had done something terribly wrong. But then Doug suddenly stopped and the way he looked at her made her tremble inside. After that, nothing unusual happened. Doug even took her out to the countryside to play. He threw the ball and she dashed after it. But when she turned back, Doug was walking away. She thought it was just another one of Doug's game when she returned with the ball. And ran into the cabin. Doug became strangely excited, seemed to truly enjoy this game with her. Soon, he brought her to the countryside again, again and again. But she always managed to find her way home. Seeing her win every time, Doug became strangely thrilled by her ability. Then he drove her even farther, three days and nights on the road from the West Coast to the East Coast. Along the way were breathtaking sights she had never seen before. He felt like I was always picking fights. Because of religious beliefs, many rural areas in India don't have toilets. But right after I squatted down, I saw my father riding by on his motorcycle, his headlights shining right on me. The moment was painfully awkward, so I quickly covered my face with my scarf and in his panic, he fell into the grass. The next day I smashed the cookware in anger over what happened. I was stuck inside and started yelling for help. People heard me and moved the cargo aside. But by the time I got out, the train had already started moving. voice_to_text: After years of trying to get pregnant, I had to choose which one of my babies would survive. My husband and I were told we would never have children. So when the doctor looked at our ultrasound and said, I'm seeing two heartbeats, I completely fell apart. We had spent five years trying everything, and my husband held my hand through every failed treatment. Until one day he said, maybe we're not meant to be parents. I told him I wasn't ready to give up. When we finally got pregnant with twins, it felt like the universe was apologizing for all those years of heartbreak. Then we went in for a check up, and the technician got quiet in that way that makes your whole body go cold. Thirty minutes later, a specialist was explaining that our babies were in serious danger. Anger because one baby was taking almost all the blood flow while the other one was dying. I asked if there was anything we could do, and she said, there's a procedure where we let Baby B pass fully now, which gives Baby A a strong chance of survival. Without intervention, both babies will die. My husband said, so we either do nothing and lose both, or we lose one to save the other, and the doctor nodded. I looked at the screen where I could see both heartbeats flickering, and said, we waited five years for them. We can't just choose. The doctor put her hand on My arm and said, I know this is impossible, but right now you have two babies dying. This is the only way one of them gets to live. We got four more opinions, and every doctor said the same thing. Both babies would die unless we let one pass. My husband grabbed my hands and said, if we wait and lose them both, it will destroy you. I said, I can't bury both of them. I won't survive that. We scheduled the procedure for Friday, and I held my belly the whole drive, telling baby be that I was so sorry. The procedure took 11 minutes, and I watched her heartbeat disappear while I silently promised her that her sister would know her name. Three months later, our daughter hope was born healthy, and I spent the first week cycling between overwhelming love and crushing guilt. I would hold her at three in the morning and whisper apologies to the daughter I would never get to hold. We didn't tell anyone what happened.

voice_to_text: My best friend told me I was too involved with her kids, so I stopped showing up completely. For three years, I'd been the one picking up Milo and Chloe from daycare when Whitney had late meetings. I taught Milo to tie his shoes, helped Chloe through her nightmare phase and kept granola bars in my car because Whitney always forgot snacks. I was there for every scraped knee, every school project deadline Whitney missed. When Milo got chicken pox, I took a week off work because Whitney couldn't handle sick children. When Chloe's goldfish died, I was the one who held her while she sobbed. Whitney was busy with yoga retreats and book club brunches. Then one Tuesday, she invited me to lunch. We need to talk, she said, pushing her salad around. Greg thinks you're overstepping. Kids call you Auntie. They ask for you when they're upset instead of me because I show up, I said quietly. Her face went cold. You're not their parent. Maybe you need some space to focus on your own life instead of living through mine. I stood up and left money for my coffee. That was the last time we spoke. First week, Milo's teacher called me three times asking why I wasn't picking him up. Whitney hadn't arranged backup care. I didn't answer. Two weeks later, Whitney texted asking if I could watch the kids for her anniversary trip. I blocked her number. A month passed, then another. I heard through Mutual friends that things were falling apart. Whitney had to quit her pottery class because she couldn't find childcare. Greg was furious about the extra daycare costs. Chloe started having accidents again, something she conquered two years ago with my help. Six months later, I ran into them at Target. Milo saw me first. His face lit up and he broke away from Whitney, running toward me with his arms out. Where did you go, he asked. Why don't you come over anymore? I knelt down, my heart breaking. I've been busy, buddy. We miss you, he said. Mommy cries a lot now and nobody makes the special sandwiches like you do. Whitney caught up, her face gaunt and exhausted. Dark circles shadowed her eyes. Can we talk, she asked, her voice small. I don't think so, I said. Standing up. You made it clear I was overstepping. I was wrong, she whispered. I didn't realize how much you did, how much they needed you, how much I needed you. You pushed me out when things were easy, I said. Now that it's hard, you want me back? Milo tugged on my sleeve. Please come back. Dad says mean things now and Mommy's always tired and nobody helps with homework anymore. I looked at Whitney, really looked at her. She'd lost weight. Her designer athleisure hung loose. The woman who'd accused me of living through her was drowning in the life she'd demanded I leave. I hope you figure it. Out I said gently then to Milo, be good, okay? Take care of your sister. I walked away as he called my name. Whitney didn't follow. I just stood there in the toy aisle holding Chloe's hand, looking lost in her own life. A year later, I heard they'd hired a full time nanny. It cost them $52,000 annually, money that strained their marriage further. Greg resented every payment, apparently mentioning often that I used to do it all for free out of love. Sometimes I still think about Milo's face that day in target, the confusion in his eyes when I left. But I Learned something important. You can't pour from an empty cup and people only value what they've lost. Whitney wanted the conviction of my devotion without the acknowledgement of my sacrifice, I never went back.

video_description: My best friend told me I was too involved with her kids, so I stopped showing up completely. #reddit #redditstories #redditreadings #redditstorytime #aita
voice_to_text: My best friend told me I was too involved with her kids, so I stopped showing up completely. I met Crystal in college and we became the kind of friends who would do anything for each other. When her husband walked out while she was six months pregnant with her second child, I moved in for three months and never really left. That was seven years ago. And I became Auntie Laney, the woman who knew her oldest was allergic to strong strawberries and terrified of thunderstorms, the woman who could get her youngest to sleep when nobody else could. I was the emergency contact at both their schools and the person who held Crystal's hand in the delivery room when her youngest came into the world. I never expected a medal for any of it because I loved those girls like they were my own and I thought Crystal under. About six months ago, Crystal started dating a guy from work and everything shifted. Her new boyfriend had opinions about me from day one, constantly asking why I was always around and suggesting it was strange for a single woman to be so attached to someone else's children. Crystal started canceling our usual weekend plans and having him handle school pickups instead, which he constantly messed up by forgetting backpacks or showing up 20 minutes late. I told myself this was just an adjustment period and tried to give them space. Then came her youngest daughter's seventh birthday party. And I overheard a conversation that changed everything. I was in the kitchen grabbing juice boxes when his voice carried in from the living room. It's honestly pathetic, he said, a woman with no family of her own playing pretend with someone else's kids. I froze and waited for Crystal to defend me. Instead, I heard her sigh. I know I've been trying to get her to back off, but she won't take a hint. I walked straight out to the backyard where she was standing. Is that really how you feel about the last seven years? She crossed her arms. He has a point. You're too involved, Laney. Maybe it's time you focused on building your own life instead of borrowing mine. I gave her exactly what she wanted and disappeared from their lives completely. Two weeks later, my phone rang and it was the elementary school telling me that Crystal's youngest was having a severe allergic reaction and they could not reach her mother. I was still listed as emergency contact, so I grabbed my keys and the Epipen I had been carrying in my purse and ran. I made it there in 12 minutes and handed over the Epipen. The nurse administered the shot while I held the oldest daughter in the hallway and let her sob into my shoulder. Twenty minutes later, Crystal finally rushed through the doors with her boyfriend trailing behind her. She spotted me and her face went hard. She pulled me into An empty classroom and got right in my face. What are you doing here? I told you to back off. I stared at her in disbelief. I just saved your daughter's life. She stepped closer. You had no right to be here. You're not her mother. Laney, stop pretending you have any claim to my children. Something in me snapped. I'm the one who noticed she was developing a peanut allergy three weeks ago. I told you about it and you said I was being dramatic. So I bought an Epipen with my own money and I called the school nurse myself to warn her. What exactly did you do, Crystal? Because.

video_description: My best friend told me I was too involved with her kids, so I stopped showing up completely. #reddit #redditstories #redditreadings #redditstorytime #aita
voice_to_text: My best friend told me I was too involved with her kids, so I stopped showing up completely. I met Crystal in college, and we became the kind of friends who would do anything for each other. When her husband walked out while she was six months pregnant with her second child, I moved in for three months and never really left. That was seven years ago, and I became Auntie Laney, the woman who knew her oldest was allergic to strawberries and terrified of thunderstorms. The woman who could get her youngest to sleep when nobody else could. I was the emergency contact at both their schools and the person who held Crystal's hand in the delivery room when her youngest came into the world. I never expected a medal for any of it, because I loved those girls like they were my own, and I thought Crystal understood that. About six months ago, Crystal started dating a guy from work, and everything shifted. Her new boyfriend had opinions about me from day one, constantly asking why I was always around and suggesting it was strange for a single woman to be so attached to someone else's children. Crystal started canceling our usual weekend plans and having him handle school pickups instead, which he constantly messed up by forgetting backpacks or showing up 20 minutes late. I told myself this was just an adjustment period and tried to give them space. Then came her youngest daughter's seventh birthday party. And I overheard a conversation that changed everything. I was in the kitchen grabbing juice boxes when his voice carried in from the living room. It's honestly pathetic, he said. A woman with no family of her own playing pretend with someone else's kids. I froze and waited for Crystal to defend me. Instead, I heard her sigh. I know I've been trying to get her to back off, but she won't take a hint. I walked straight out to the backyard where she was standing. Is that really how you feel about the last seven years? She crossed her arms. He has a point. You're too involved, Laney. Maybe it's time you focused on building your own life instead of borrowing mine. I gave her exactly what she wanted and disappeared from their lives completely. Two weeks later, my phone rang, and it was the elementary school telling me that Crystal's youngest was having a severe allergic reaction and they could not reach her mother. I was still listed as emergency contact, so I grabbed my keys and the epi pen I had been carrying in my purse and ran. I made it there in 12 minutes and handed over the EPI pen. The nurse administered the shot while I held the oldest daughter in the hallway and let her sob into my shoulder. Twenty minutes later, Crystal finally rushed through the doors with her boyfriend trailing behind her. She spotted me, and her face went hard. She pulled Me? Into an empty classroom and got right in my face. What are you doing here? I told you to back off. I stared at her in disbelief. I just saved your daughter's life. She stepped closer. You had no right to be here. You're not her mother, Laney. Stop pretending you have any claim to my children. Something in me snapped. I'm the one who noticed she was developing a peanut allergy. Three weeks. I told you about it, and you said I was being dramatic. So I bought an Epipen with my own money, and I called the school nurse myself to warn her. What exactly did you do, crystal? Because
